<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://espn.go.com/outdoors/conservation/s/f_fea_bass_ethics.html" target="top">espn.go.com/outdoors/conservation/s/f_fea_bass_ethics.html</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> <p><a href="http://www.geocities.com/rdvtavssvjnm/BASS/BASSx.html">
RICK'S ULTIMATE BASS FISHING</font></a></b></font><br /><br /></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bfishtalkandfishingreports.showUserPublicProfile?gid=fishchris1@fishtalkandfishingreports>FishChris1</A></span><br> Posts: 24<br> <font color=#FFFF00>(1/23/04 11:17 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/ffishtalkandfishingreportsfrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=25.topic&index=29>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   That is an excellent article.......</span><hr size=1> Very accurate. In fact, I agree on all counts..... except one.....<br>
<br>
When author Marcantonio says, &quot;Personally, fishing for bedding bass is not much of a challenge anymore, as once you figure out how to catch them, it can be ridiculously easy&quot;....... <br>
HA ! He obviously hasn't bedfished for giant Florida strains in my neck of the woods ! Just sighting a big one on a bed, that will stick around for more than .2 seconds after she has sighted you, can be a huge challenge in itself ! <br>
So after three 10 hour fishing days, you finally find one that is relatively glued. You make your cast.... in runs the male.... you stick him, and she spooks off :-( Urgggg..... but after 15 minutes of sitting as still as a statue, she reluctantly comes back. You make a cast, and she acts interested, but here comes the male again..... he picks up your lure, but you don't set on him. (or you can try sticking him again and putting him in your livewell) and so she spooks again. Twenty minutes later, here she comes again...... but so does a breeze ! Urggg.... Now your fishing for nothing more than a &quot;blur&quot;.... After fishing for her for 3 more hours straight, she finally cruises off, but she did so during that last wind gust, leaving you wondering how long you have been fishing an empty bed ! <br>
<br>
Oh sure, on rare occasion I have stuck a double digit bass in 15 minutes or less, but typically, I spend an average of 2 hours on a fish before either landing it, or losing it during the fight. Of course there are many trips (probably 60% of the time) when I don't even have that much of a chance at a good one, in the first place. I have spent as much as 8 hours on a single fish, during a trip..... AND NEVER GOT HER TO GO ! (those are the rough ones) and I have spent nearly 8 hours on a single fish before I finally caught it..... which of course made it all worth it :-)<br>
<br>
One particular fish comes to mind..... A big one which was &quot;very loosely&quot; relating to a spawning area &quot;after the spawn&quot; (nobody had been able to entice her, even during the height of the spawn, although I think most of the trophy bass anglers knew where she was hanging out, and had been hammering on her daily). Personally, I spent 6 sessions with her, on 3 different trips, which lasted from 1 to 5 hours at a time (maybe about 15 hours total) before I finally stuck her on a wad of crawlers. Totally spawned out, she still went 14.1 lbs, which in my opinion, made all of those hours totally worth it, and then some :-) But to say she was easy ????? Yea' right ! <br>
<br>
BTW, my favorite sight fishing lake gets a ton of pressure put on it every Spring, yet by April there are massive clouds of bass fry swirling everywhere ! Obviously no problems with recruitment.<br>
<br>
Peace,<br>
Fish Chris<br>
