#2- On the subject of boats from other states crossing the line.  I love it!  We have a great fishery that is not overrun like some of the more popular states like Fla, Tenn, Ky.  And most of the weigh ins I have watched are held with the fish in mind. We are a poor state when it comes to revenue for Natl Resources.  We need the out of state license fees.  Our DNR people are one of the lowest paid in the country and we keep losing the good ones to more affluent areas. Our state govt at times does not even realize that we have a fishery. Fisherpeople need a champion in Ind.<br>
Enough of that soapbox stuff.  Come fish our waters and I will fish yours and rest assured, your fish are safe with me!! <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bfishtalkandfishingreports.showUserPublicProfile?gid=fishchris1@fishtalkandfishingreports>FishChris1</A></span><br> Posts: 31<br> <font color=#FFFF00>(2/22/04 12:55 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/ffishtalkandfishingreportsfrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=25.topic&index=34>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Well ya' know what ?</span><hr size=1> I totally agree with Indiana Jack when he said, &gt; but I do feel that bed fishing has its effects &lt; .......<br>
Well sure it does..... &quot;As does fishing in general&quot; !!!!<br>
But so long as your particular fisheries are not suffering from a lack of recruitment, then it should be your choice, as a licensed angler, to fish with any / all techniques that fall within your state regulations. <br>
<br>
I've said it before, but I feel compelled to say it again;<br>
Please use common sense when handling large bass, and above all else remember one thing.... Whether you (permanently) remove a big female bass this Spring during the spawn, or later this Summer or Fall, she surely won't be there spawning next Spring !<br>
<br>
For what it's worth,<br>
Fish Chris <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> Mike</span><br> <span class=usertitle>Unregistered User</span><br>   <font color=#FFFF00>(3/5/04 12:37 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/ffishtalkandfishingreportsfrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=25.topic&index=35>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Question on the spawning bass?</span><hr size=1> Hello Everyone. <br>
<br>
I have a question regarding the male and female relationship in size to each other.  Is it true that if you spot a large male on a bed that the female will also be large and not far off?  Same thing being said for smaller males.  Smaller male equals smaller female?  Reason I ask is when site fishing you usually spot the male around the nest, but not the female.  All help appreciated.<br>
